initial_story:
The Eurovision Song Contest is just around the corner and this year, it's taking place in Malmo, Sweden.

You can find out all about the event right here.

The UK's entry for 2024 is Olly Alexander who'll be performing his song, Dizzy.

But how's he feeling ahead of the big night, where he'll perform in front of 200 million people!

De-Graft sat down with him to find out all about his preparation for the competition.

The Eurovision Song contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.
stories: Olly Alexander laughed as he talked about the pressure of performing in the Eurovision Song Contest. "I'm feeling a mix of emotions, to be honest. There's a lot of excitement, but also a lot of nerves. It's a huge platform and I want to do it justice. But I'm also feeling quite confident, I've been working hard on my performance and I think I've got a great song."

"I mean, I've always loved Eurovision and to be a part of it is just an incredible honour. I've been watching it since I was a kid and to think that I'm going to be performing on that stage is just surreal. But at the same time, I know that the stakes are high and I want to make sure that I give the best performance possible. I've been rehearsing non-stop and I'm feeling really prepared, so I'm hoping that all that hard work will pay off."

"I've also been thinking a lot about the song, and I'm really proud of how it's coming along. It's a bit of a risk, I know, but I think it's exactly what the contest needs - something fresh and exciting. And the team I've assembled is just incredible, from the writers to the producers to the dancers, everyone is so talented and dedicated. I'm really excited to see how it all comes together on the night. Fingers crossed, of course!"

"I've been visualizing the performance in my head, and I think it's going to be a real showstopper. The combination of the music, the choreography, and the costumes is going to be just amazing. And I've got a few tricks up my sleeve that I think will really wow the judges and the audience. I'm just hoping that everything goes smoothly on the night, no technical issues or anything like that, and that we can really bring it home."

"I've been rehearsing for weeks, and I'm feeling really confident about the routine. I've got a great team behind me, and I know they're all just as excited as I am to get out there and perform. I've been thinking about what I want to say in my introduction, too - I want to make a strong impression from the start. And of course, I've been working on my transitions between moves, making sure they're seamless and fluid. I just want to make sure I can let loose and enjoy the moment, rather than worrying about anything going wrong. Fingers crossed it all comes together on the night!"

"I've been visualizing the crowd's reaction, imagining the rush of adrenaline as I step onto the stage. I've also been practicing my breathing exercises, trying to calm my nerves and focus on the music. My teammates have been a huge support, reminding me that we've all put in the work and are ready for this. I just need to trust myself and trust the routine. "I can almost smell the sweat and feel the energy of the audience as I take my first step onto the stage. We're all in this together, and together we're unstoppable. Let's do this!"
